description:
secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs:286-292:

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn integration_roundtrip() {
    if std::env::var("SECRETX_KEYRING_INTEGRATION_TESTS").as_deref() != Ok("1") {
        return;
    }
    // ... actual test
}
```

When the env var is unset (the CI default unless explicitly opted in), the function returns `()` and the test reports as PASSED. `cargo test -p secretx-keyring` shows '8 passed' regardless of whether any integration coverage actually executed. Reviewing CI logs gives no signal that the integration path was skipped.

Compare: `#[ignore]` on the test would make it report as 'ignored' in test output, and CI logs would show clearly that `integration_roundtrip` was not executed. `#[ignore]` plus an explicit opt-in via `cargo test -- --include-ignored` is the conventional pattern.

Trigger: maintainer relies on green CI to gate releases. Cross-platform CI runs without setting the env var, all integration tests silently skip, a regression in the spawn_blocking JoinError mapping or in the keyring crate's API ships undetected.

Resolution: switch to `#[ignore = "requires SECRETX_KEYRING_INTEGRATION_TESTS=1 and kernel keyring"]` and run with `cargo test -- --ignored` (or `--include-ignored`) in the dedicated integration job. The env var becomes redundant since `#[ignore]` is the ignore mechanism.
